"# Chapter 11 — Text field, color picker, live-code

Three widgets in one chapter, because they naturally cluster. Text field writes strings. Color picker writes colors. Live-code shows the emitted Scheme as an editable text panel — the widget whose sole job is to make the round-trip visible.

## 11.1 The text field

```
(composer/text-field :bind . options)
```

- `:bind` — path. Where the string writes.
- `:label` — string, optional.
- `:value` — string, optional. Default `\"\"`.

The widget writes a string to the bind path. That is all.

Emit:

```
(composer/text-field :bind (quote (cart/meta :title))
                     :label \"Cart title\" :value \"my song\")
```

The current `:value` is included so a reload lands the field with the user's typing.

## 11.2 ASCII mockup — a text field

```
Cart title: \"my song\"
```

Label, colon, quoted string. That's the TUI rendering.

## 11.3 The color picker

```
(composer/color-picker :bind . options)
```

- `:bind` — path. Where the color writes.
- `:palette` — symbol, optional. If provided, the picker restricts to the named palette and emits a symbol; if omitted, the picker emits a hex string.

## 11.4 Color picker emit

With a palette:

```
(composer/color-picker :bind (quote (cart/theme :bg))
                       :value (quote crimson))
```

The value is a symbol from the palette. The widget declaration includes the current `:value`.

Without a palette:

```
(composer/color-picker :bind (quote (cart/theme :bg))
                       :value \"#dc143c\")
```

The value is a hex string.

The composer stores whichever shape you set. Palette-mode gives you symbolic names (crimson, forestgreen, coral); freeform mode gives you hex strings.

## 11.5 The HTML-16 palette in the color picker

Combined with the v1.1 named-color infrastructure, a color picker bound to the html-16 palette lets kids pick from 16 named CSS colors:

```scheme
(composer/color-picker :bind '(cart/theme :bg) :palette 'html-16)
```

Emit:

```
(composer/color-picker :bind (quote (cart/theme :bg))
                       :value (quote black))
```

Default is 'black when the palette is html-16. Hand-edit to `:value 'crimson` and reload — the picker shows crimson selected.

Look up the actual color a symbol maps to: `(color/named 'crimson)` returns `\"#dc143c\"`. The picker knows this because the palette carries the mapping.

## 11.6 The live-code widget

```
(composer/live-code :bind . options)
```

- `:bind` — path. Where the source string writes.

The live-code widget shows the emitted Scheme form as an editable text panel. Edits to the text propagate back — the widget re-parses and the other widgets in the canvas re-render to match.

This is the round-trip made visible. See the emit, edit the emit, see the widgets follow.

## 11.7 ASCII mockup — a live-code panel

```
live-code: \"(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart)))...\"
```

The TUI shows a truncated preview. The full Curator canvas shows a scrollable syntax-highlighted panel with the full emitted form, editable in place.

## 11.8 Why live-code exists

The composer promises: every widget round-trips through Scheme. The live-code widget SHOWS the Scheme. A kid clicking a piano-roll cell sees the note appear in the live-code panel as a new `(note :pitch ...)` form. A kid typing into the live-code panel sees the piano-roll cell update. The two views are the same data, edited from either side.

For programmers, this is the composer's confession: the tool is not hiding anything from you. Everything you can do with a widget you can do by typing Scheme.

For kids, this is the composer's invitation: the code is right there, don't fear it, poke it, watch what happens.

## 11.9 A worked example — a text-field + color-picker canvas

```scheme
(composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/meta))
  (composer/text-field :bind '(cart/meta :title) :label \"Cart title\" :value \"my song\")
  (composer/text-field :bind '(cart/meta :author) :label \"Author\" :value \"\")
  (composer/color-picker :bind '(cart/theme :bg) :palette 'html-16)
  (composer/color-picker :bind '(cart/theme :fg) :palette 'html-16))
```

Four children: two text fields for metadata, two color pickers for background and foreground theme colors.

Emit:

```
(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart/meta)))
  (composer/text-field :bind (quote (cart/meta :title))
                       :label \"Cart title\" :value \"my song\")
  (composer/text-field :bind (quote (cart/meta :author))
                       :label \"Author\" :value \"\")
  (composer/color-picker :bind (quote (cart/theme :bg))
                         :value (quote black))
  (composer/color-picker :bind (quote (cart/theme :fg))
                         :value (quote black)))
```

Save, hand-edit, reload — the fields update.

## 11.10 The live-code widget composes with the others

The most instructive canvas mixes a live-code widget with other widgets:

```scheme
(composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/main))
  (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind '(cart/main :bpm) :min 60 :max 240 :step 1)
  (composer/toggle :bind '(cart/opts :muted) :label \"Muted\")
  (composer/live-code :bind '(cart/main)))
```

Three children. The live-code widget shows the emitted form of the canvas. Move the slider, the emit updates, the live-code panel updates. Edit the number in the live-code panel, the slider moves.

Kids who click the slider learn what Scheme looks like. Kids who type into the live-code panel learn what a slider is. Same file. Same round-trip. Two teachers.

## 11.11 What to remember from this chapter

- Text field writes a string to a bind path. `:label` and `:value` are optional.
- Color picker writes a color to a bind path. With `:palette`, emits a symbol; without, emits a hex string.
- The v1.1 html-16 palette gives 16 named CSS colors for the picker.
- Live-code shows the emitted Scheme form as an editable panel. Edits propagate back — the widgets re-render.
- Combine live-code with other widgets to make the round-trip visible in the UI itself.

Chapter 12 introduces the 16-voice mixer that composer v1.1 added.
")
